# Notation and key formulas

## Variables (for $s$ stages)

| Symbol | Definition |
|--------|-----------|
| $s$ | Number of demographic stages (3 here) |
| $D_i$ | Fraction of the population in stage $i$; $\sum_i D_i = 1$ |
| $u_{ji}$ | Transition rate: probability a stage-$i$ plant at year $t$ is in stage $j$ at year $t+1$ |
| $u_{\cdot i} = \sum_j u_{ji}$ | Total annual survival rate of stage $i$ |
| $\bar{u} = \sum_i D_i\,u_{\cdot i}$ | Population-average annual survival |
| $\overline{u^2} = \sum_i D_i\,u_{\cdot i}^2$ | Stage-weighted second moment of survival |
| $F_i$ | Newborns produced per plant in stage $i$ per year |
| $r_i = F_i\,D_i$ | Contribution of newborns from stage $i$ to the whole population |
| $d_i \in [0,1]$ | Clonal reproduction rate of stage $i$; sexual rate $= 1 - d_i$ |
| $(V_k/\bar{k})_i$ | Variance/mean ratio of sexual (gametic) reproductive output, stage $i$ |
| $(V_c/\bar{c})_i$ | Variance/mean ratio of clonal reproductive output, stage $i$ |
| $a$ | Deviation from Hardy-Weinberg proportions ($a = 0$ under random mating) |
| $L$ | Generation time (defined via age-by-stage iteration; see Section 2.4) |

> **Note on $\bar{u}^2$ vs $\overline{u^2}$**: these are different quantities.
> $\bar{u}^2 = \bigl(\sum_i D_i\,u_{\cdot i}\bigr)^2$ is the square of the mean survival,
> while $\overline{u^2} = \sum_i D_i\,u_{\cdot i}^2$ is the mean of squared survivals.
> Their difference $\overline{u^2} - \bar{u}^2 \geq 0$ captures stage-to-stage
> variation in survival and is the first source of genetic drift in Eq. 5.

## The one-year variance of allele-frequency change (Eq. 5)

Let $p$ be the frequency of an allele and $pq = p(1-p)$. At demographic equilibrium, with $pq$ and $a$ assumed equal across all stages, the **one-year variance** of allele-frequency change is (Eq. 5 of Yonezawa 2000):

$$
V(\Delta p)
= \frac{pq}{2N}\left\{(1+a)\big(\overline{u^2} - \bar{u}^{\,2}\big)
+ \frac{1}{2}(1 - \bar{u})\big[\mathrm{Avr}(S) + \mathrm{Avr}(A\delta)\big]\right\}
$$

The terms $S_i$ and $A_i$ are defined as (paper p. 2008):

$$
S_i = (1 - a) + (1 + a)\left(\frac{V_k}{\bar{k}}\right)_i
$$

$$
A_i = 2(1 + a)\left(\frac{V_c}{\bar{c}}\right)_i - S_i
$$

> **Important**: the paper defines $A_i$ by subtracting $S_i$ **once**:
> $A_i = 2(1+a)(V_c/\bar{c})_i - S_i$.
> This is implemented exactly in `compute_Ne_general()` below.

The recruitment-weighted averages over all stages are:
$$
\mathrm{Avr}(S) = \frac{\sum_i r_i\,S_i}{\sum_i r_i}, \qquad
\mathrm{Avr}(A\delta) = \frac{\sum_i r_i\,A_i\,d_i}{\sum_i r_i}
$$

The **first term** in Eq. 5 captures variance from **survival and stage transitions**;
the **second term** captures variance from **recruitment** (sexual + clonal),
weighted by each stage's contribution of newborns $r_i$.

## General generation-time effective size $N_e$ (Eq. 6)

Assuming census size $N$ is constant over the generation, the product $V(\Delta p) \times L$ gives the generation-time variance of allele frequency. Setting this equal to the Wright-Fisher variance $pq/(2N_e)$ and solving gives (Eq. 6):

$$
\boxed{N_e = \frac{2N}{V \cdot L}}
$$

where

$$
V = 2(1+a)\big(\overline{u^2} - \bar{u}^{\,2}\big) + (1-\bar{u})\big[\mathrm{Avr}(S) + \mathrm{Avr}(A\delta)\big]
$$

## Clonal-dominant Poisson special case (Eq. 9 → Eq. 10)

In *Fritillaria*, all reproduction is effectively clonal ($d_i \approx 1$), Poisson-distributed
($(V_c/\bar{c})_i = 1$), and random mating applies ($a = 0$). Under these assumptions
$\mathrm{Avr}(S) + \mathrm{Avr}(A\delta) = 2\,\mathrm{Avr}(V_c/\bar{c}) = 2$,
so $V = 2(1 - \bar{u})$, yielding (Eq. 10):

$$
\boxed{N_e \approx \frac{N}{(1 - \bar{u})\,L}} \qquad \text{(Eq. 10)}
$$

## Annual effective size $N_y$ (Eq. 11)

For year-by-year drift, the **annual** effective size is (Eq. 11):

$$
\boxed{N_y = \frac{N}{1 - \bar{u}}} \qquad \text{(Eq. 11)}
$$

As $\bar{u} \to 1$ (very high annual survival), $N_y \to \infty$, meaning less drift per year.
Note that $N_e/N = (N_y/N)\,/\,L$.

## Generation time $L$ — Yonezawa definition

The paper defines $L$ as the mean age of reproduction (sexual **or** clonal),
computed by iterating the transition matrix (paper p. 2008–2009):

$$
L = \frac{\sum_{x=1}^{500} x\,m_x\,\ell_x}{\sum_{x=1}^{500} m_x\,\ell_x}
$$

where $\ell_x = \sum_j u_{j|x}$ is the probability a newborn survives to age $x$,
$m_x = \sum_j F_j\,u_{j|x}$ is average reproduction at age $x$,
and $u_{j|x}$ is the $(j,1)$ element of $[\mathbf{u}_{ji}]^x$.

> **Note on L methods**: `popbio::generation.time()` uses Caswell's (1989)
> sensitivity-based formula — a related but different definition.
> We implement the native Yonezawa formula and compare both values below.
> For the *Fritillaria* populations they agree closely.

